<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="122" name="The d- and f-Block Elements">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Elements in which d-orbitals are progressively filled are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Transition elements</option><option id="B">Noble gases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found in groups 3 to 12.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition elements are located between ____ and ____ blocks.</text>
            <option id="A">s and p</option><option id="B">p and f</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Central part of periodic table.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>General electronic configuration of d-block elements is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(n-1)d^1-10 ns^1-2</option><option id="B">ns^2 np^1-6</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>d-orbitals are filled in penultimate shell.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is NOT strictly a transition element?</text>
            <option id="A">Zinc (Zn)</option><option id="B">Iron (Fe)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Zn, Cd, Hg have completely filled d-orbitals in ground and common oxidation states.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The 3d transition series starts from ____ and ends at ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sc (21) to Zn (30)</option><option id="B">Ti to Cu</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>First transition series.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The 4d transition series starts from ____ and ends at ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Y (39) to Cd (48)</option><option id="B">Zr to Ag</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Second transition series.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The 5d transition series starts from ____ and ends at ____.</text>
            <option id="A">La (57), Hf (72) to Hg (80)</option><option id="B">Ba to Au</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Includes lanthanoids gap.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition metals have high ____ and ____ points.</text>
            <option id="A">Melting and Boiling</option><option id="B">Vapor pressure</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to strong metallic bonding (d-electron involvement).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition metals show ____ oxidation states.</text>
            <option id="A">Variable</option><option id="B">Single</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to comparable energies of ns and (n-1)d electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element shows the maximum number of oxidation states in 3d series?</text>
            <option id="A">Manganese (Mn)</option><option id="B">Iron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Shows states from +2 to +7.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnetic property of transition metal ions is mainly due to ____ electrons.</text>
            <option id="A">Unpaired d</option><option id="B">Paired p</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Paramagnetism increases with number of unpaired electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition metals and their compounds act as good ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Catalysts</option><option id="B">Insulators</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to variable oxidation states and complex formation ability.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Most transition metal compounds are ____ in solid or solution form.</text>
            <option id="A">Colored</option><option id="B">Colorless</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to d-d transitions.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition metals have a tendency to form ____ compounds.</text>
            <option id="A">Complex / Coordination</option><option id="B">Simple ionic only</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Small size and high charge density.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Interstitial compounds are formed when small atoms like H, C, N are trapped in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Voids of metal crystal lattice</option><option id="B">Nucleus</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Non-stoichiometric in nature.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Alloys are ____ mixtures of two or more metals.</text>
            <option id="A">Homogeneous</option><option id="B">Heterogeneous</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Transition metals form many alloys due to similar sizes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lanthanoids (4f series) follow which element?</text>
            <option id="A">Lanthanum (La)</option><option id="B">Actinium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ce (58) to Lu (71).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Actinoids (5f series) follow which element?</text>
            <option id="A">Actinium (Ac)</option><option id="B">Lanthanum</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Th (90) to Lr (103).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>General electronic configuration of f-block elements is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(n-2)f^1-14 (n-1)d^0-1 ns^2</option><option id="B">ns^2 np^6</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Involvement of pre-penultimate shells.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Decrease in atomic/ionic radii of lanthanoids with atomic number is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lanthanoid contraction</option><option id="B">Expansion</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to poor shielding by f-electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Most common oxidation state of lanthanoids is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">+3</option><option id="B">+2</option><option id="C">+4</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Quite stable for most elements.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Actinoids show ____ range of oxidation states than lanthanoids.</text>
            <option id="A">Wider</option><option id="B">Narrower</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to small energy gap between 5f, 6d and 7s levels.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following lanthanoids is radioactive?</text>
            <option id="A">Promethium (Pm)</option><option id="B">Europium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Artificial element.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Potassium dichromate formula is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">K2Cr2O7</option><option id="B">KMnO4</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Orange crystalline solid.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Potassium permanganate formula is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">KMnO4</option><option id="B">K2Cr2O7</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Deep purple solid.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dichromate ion (Cr2O7 2-) has ____ color.</text>
            <option id="A">Orange</option><option id="B">Yellow</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exhibits pH dependency (chromate vs dichromate).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Chromate ion (CrO4 2-) has ____ color.</text>
            <option id="A">Yellow</option><option id="B">Orange</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stable in alkaline medium.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>KMnO4 acts as an ____ agent in acid, neutral and alkaline media.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxidizing</option><option id="B">Reducing</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Versatile reagent in Titrimetry.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cu(I) ion is unstable in aqueous solution and undergoes ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Disproportionation (to Cu(II) and Cu)</option><option id="B">Reduction</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>2Cu+ -> Cu2+ + Cu.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Scandium (Z=21) shows only one oxidation state that is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">+3</option><option id="B">+2</option><option id="C">+4</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Noble gas config reached.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A substance is paramagnetic if it has ____ electrons.</text>
            <option id="A">Unpaired</option><option id="B">Paired</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Attracted by magnetic field.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnetic moment (μ) is calculated by ____ formula.</text>
            <option id="A">sqrt(n(n+2)) BM</option><option id="B">n BM</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Spin-only formula.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Color of Fe2+ ion is generally ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Green</option><option id="B">Yellow / Brown</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pale green.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Color of Fe3+ ion is generally ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yellow / Brown</option><option id="B">Green</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to charge transfer or hydrolysis.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Standard reduction potential of Cu2+/Cu is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Positive (+0.34 V)</option><option id="B">Negative</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unique among 3d metals.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Highest fluoride of Mn is MnF4, but highest oxide is Mn2O7. Why?</text>
            <option id="A">Oxygen forms multiple bonds</option><option id="B">Fluorine is too large</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ability of oxygen to stabilize high states by pi-bonding.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Mischmetal is an alloy consisting of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lanthanoid metal (~95%) and Iron (~5%)</option><option id="B">Steel</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used in lighter flints.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition metals are harder than s-block metals due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Covalent character of metallic bond (d-participation)</option><option id="B">Atomic mass</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>More electrons available for bonding.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element has the lowest melting point in d-block?</text>
            <option id="A">Mercury (Hg)</option><option id="B">Zinc</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Liquid at room temperature.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Enthalpy of atomization of transition metals is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">High</option><option id="B">Low</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Strong inter-atomic forces.</explanation>
        </question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Cr2+ is a reducing agent while Mn3+ is an oxidizing agent? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (stable d3 config for Cr3+)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cr2+ loses e- to reach d3 (stable in octahedral). Mn3+ gains e- to reach d4/d5.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which ion has magnetic moment 3.87 BM?</text>
            <option id="A">Cr3+ (n=3)</option><option id="B">Fe2+ (n=4)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>μ = sqrt(3*5) = sqrt(15).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition metals show high enthalpy of atomization because of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Participation of (n-1)d and ns electrons in bonding</option><option id="B">Large size</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Strong metallic and covalent bonding.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Reason for Lanthanoid contraction is ____ shielding of 4f electrons.</text>
            <option id="A">Poor</option><option id="B">Perfect</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>f-orbitals are very diffused.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Elements of 4d and 5d series have similar radii (e.g. Zr and Hf) due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lanthanoid contraction</option><option id="B">Actinoid contraction</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increase due to shell is offset by contraction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which lanthanoid is used as an oxidizing agent in analytical chemistry?</text>
            <option id="A">Ce4+ (Cerium IV)</option><option id="B">Lu3+</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tends to go to stable +3 state.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnetic moment of Mn2+ (Z=25) is ____ BM.</text>
            <option id="A">5.92</option><option id="B">4.90</option><option id="C">1.73</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>d5 config has 5 unpaired electrons. sqrt(5*7) = 5.92.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnetic moment of Fe2+ (Z=26) is ____ BM.</text>
            <option id="A">4.90</option><option id="B">5.92</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>d6 config has 4 unpaired electrons. sqrt(4*6) = 4.90.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Color of Sc3+ and Ti4+ ions is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Colorless</option><option id="B">Violet</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>d0 configuration (no d-d transitions possible).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Color of Zn2+ and Cu+ ions is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Colorless</option><option id="B">Blue</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>d10 configuration (filled d-orbitals).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition metals form complexes because of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Small size, High charge, Empty d-orbitals</option><option id="B">Large size</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can accept electron pairs from ligands.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Interstitial compounds are generally ____ than pure metals.</text>
            <option id="A">Harder</option><option id="B">Softer</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Small atoms lock the layers of metal atoms.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Chemical twins are elements with similar ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Size and properties (e.g. Zr, Hf)</option><option id="B">Atomic number</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Result of lanthanoid contraction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In acid medium, MnO4- is reduced to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mn2+</option><option id="B">MnO2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gain of 5 electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In neutral or weakly alkaline medium, MnO4- is reduced to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">MnO2</option><option id="B">Mn2+</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gain of 3 electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In strongly alkaline medium, MnO4- is reduced to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">MnO4 2- (Manganate)</option><option id="B">Mn2+</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gain of 1 electron.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Chromyl chloride test is used for detection of ____ ion.</text>
            <option id="A">Chloride (Cl-)</option><option id="B">Bromide</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Red vapors of CrO2Cl2 are formed.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Potassium dichromate reacts with KI in acid to liberate ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Iodine (I2)</option><option id="B">KMnO4</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dichromate is an oxidizing agent.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which is a stronger oxidizing agent in aqueous solution: Ti2+, V2+ or Cr2+?</text>
            <option id="A">None (they are reducing agents)</option><option id="B">Ti2+</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Early transition ions are mostly reducing.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Manganese shows oxidation states up to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">+7</option><option id="B">+6</option><option id="C">+5</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses all 5 d-electrons and 2 s-electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Cu2+ is more stable than Cu+ in water due to high ____ enthalpy.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydration</option><option id="B">Ionization</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Compensates for high second ionization enthalpy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following has highest magnetic moment?</text>
            <option id="A">Fe3+ (d5)</option><option id="B">Fe2+ (d6)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>d5 high spin has 5 unpaired electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation of oxalic acid by KMnO4 in acid medium gives ____ gas.</text>
            <option id="A">CO2</option><option id="B">O2</option><option id="C">CO</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard redox titration reaction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Color of KMnO4 is due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Charge transfer (L to M)</option><option id="B">d-d transition</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mn is in +7 state (d0), no d-electrons available for d-d.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Actinoids show irregular electronic configs due to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Very small energy difference between 5f, 6d and 7s</option><option id="B">Relativistic effects</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Leads to easy promotion of electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Actinoid contraction is greater than lanthanoid contraction because of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Worse shielding by 5f than 4f</option><option id="B">Better shielding</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>5f orbitals are more diffused.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element of 3d series has highest melting point?</text>
            <option id="A">Chromium (Cr)</option><option id="B">Iron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Strong metallic bonds (d5s1 config contribution).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition metals have a tendency to show ____ catalytic activity.</text>
            <option id="A">High</option><option id="B">Low</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mainly due to variable oxidation states.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of moles of KMnO4 needed to oxidize 1 mole of ferrous oxalate in acid?</text>
            <option id="A">3/5</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fe2+ -> Fe3+ (1e) and C2O4 2- -> 2CO2 (2e). Total 3e needed. MnO4- takes 5e.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>K2Cr2O7 is preferred over Na2Cr2O7 as a primary standard because it is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Not hygroscopic</option><option id="B">More soluble</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Na2Cr2O7 absorbs moisture from air.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Structure of Pyrolusite (ore of Mn) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">MnO2</option><option id="B">Mn2O3</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Principal source of Manganese.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Maximum atomic radius among 3d metals is of ____ (considering start/end).</text>
            <option id="A">Scandium / Zinc (Zn is larger than Cu?)</option><option id="B">Iron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Radii decrease till middle, then slightly increase due to repulsion.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnetic moment of Ti3+ (Z=22) is ____ BM.</text>
            <option id="A">1.73</option><option id="B">2.83</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>d1 config has 1 unpaired electron. sqrt(1*3) = 1.73.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnetic moment of V2+ (Z=23) is ____ BM.</text>
            <option id="A">3.87</option><option id="B">2.83</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>d3 config has 3 unpaired electrons. sqrt(3*5) = 3.87.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnetic moment of Ni2+ (Z=28) is ____ BM.</text>
            <option id="A">2.83</option><option id="B">3.87</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>d8 config has 2 unpaired electrons. sqrt(2*4) = 2.83.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Reason for color of [Sc(H2O)6]3+? ____.</text>
